+# Security False-Positive Analysis — CVE-2026-32739 (libheif, Debian trixie)
+
+**CVE-2026-32739** — *not-affected (false positive)*
+
+> This is a companion issue to CVE-2026-32738 (above). It lives in the **same HEIF
+> image-sequence / track parsing subsystem** and has the **same root cause and the same
+> `not-affected` verdict** for trixie.
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| CVE | CVE-2026-32739 |
+| Package | `libheif` |
+| Distribution | Debian 13 (trixie) |
+| Shipped version | `1.19.8` (`1.19.8-1`) |
+| Verdict | **not-affected** — vulnerable code not present |
+| Reason class | Feature introduced in the next minor release (1.20.0), after the shipped version |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Summary
+
+CVE-2026-32739 reports a denial-of-service (infinite loop) issue in libheif's **HEIF
+image-sequence / track parsing** subsystem. The advisory states it affects *"versions
+1.21.2 and below"* and is fixed in `1.22.0`.
+
+Debian trixie ships **libheif 1.19.8**. The vulnerable code — the `stts`
+(decoding-time-to-sample) box parser and its `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()` method —
+**does not exist in 1.19.8**. As with CVE-2026-32738, the entire image-sequence / track
+reading subsystem (`libheif/sequences/`) was introduced in **libheif 1.20.0**, the release
+after the one trixie shipped.
+
+The "1.21.2 and below" wording is **numerically true but misleading**: `1.19.8 < 1.21.2`,
+yet the loop the exploit depends on is absent. A crafted "HEIF sequence file" cannot reach
+the vulnerable logic in 1.19.8 — the `stts` box is treated as an unknown box and skipped.
+
+**Conclusion: CVE-2026-32739 is a false positive for trixie and should be marked
+`not-affected`.**
+
+---
+
+## 2. What the CVE describes
+
+> In versions 1.21.2 and below, a crafted 800-byte HEIF sequence file causes an infinite
+> loop in `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()`, consuming 100% CPU indefinitely with zero
+> progress, leading to DoS. The loop has no iteration limit or timeout and is triggered
+> during file open (parsing) — before any user interaction or image decoding. The process
+> stays alive (no crash, no error logged), making it invisible to crash-based monitoring.
+> This issue has been fixed in version 1.22.0.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why this cannot occur in trixie (1.19.8)
+
+`Box_stts` (the *decoding-time-to-sample* box) and its `get_sample_duration()` method are
+part of the same track-reading machinery as the `stsc`/`Chunk` code from CVE-2026-32738.
+They live in `libheif/sequences/seq_boxes.cc`, a file that **does not exist** in 1.19.8.
+The vulnerability requires the following constructs, none of which exist in 1.19.8:
+
+| Construct required by the CVE | Present in libheif 1.19.8? |
+|-------------------------------|----------------------------|
+| `stts` box parsing (`Box_stts`) | **No** |
+| `Box_stts::get_sample_duration()` method | **No** |
+| Time-to-sample iteration / sample-duration lookup | **No** |
+
+Because 1.19.8 has no track-reading subsystem, the `stts` box is an **unrecognized box**
+and is skipped by its declared size during parsing. There is no loop to enter, so the
+"infinite loop during file open" cannot happen.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Source verification
+
+The vulnerable subsystem was introduced in `v1.20.0`. Verified directly against the tagged
+source trees:
+
+```text
+# trixie's version — no matches (grep exit status 1)
+$ git grep -nE "Box_stts|get_sample_duration" v1.19.8 -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(no matches)
+
+# the directory that holds the vulnerable code does not exist in 1.19.8
+$ git ls-tree -r --name-only v1.19.8 | grep -iE "sequence|track|chunk"
+(no sequence/track/chunk source files in v1.19.8)
+
+# the next release (1.20.0) is where it first appears
+$ git grep -nE "Box_stts|get_sample_duration" v1.20.0 -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+v1.20.0:libheif/sequences/seq_boxes.cc:597:uint32_t Box_stts::get_sample_duration(uint32_t sample_idx)
+...
+```
+
+Both symbols named by the CVE are absent from 1.19.8 and first appear in 1.20.0.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Recommended triage entry
+
+```
+[trixie] - libheif <not-affected> (Image-sequence/track parsing — Box_stts —
+introduced in 1.20.0; trixie ships 1.19.8 which predates the feature)
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. Scope and caveats
+
+- This analysis is verified against the upstream **libheif 1.19.8** tag, which matches the
+  version Debian trixie ships (`1.19.8-1`, per `sources.debian.org`).
+- The affected range is **1.20.0 → 1.21.2** (fixed in 1.22.0). Debian **sid / forky ship
+  `1.21.2-4`, which DOES contain the vulnerable code** — those suites are **affected**
+  (real vulnerability, not a false positive) and require the 1.22.0 fix. Only trixie
+  (1.19.8) and bookworm (1.15.1) predate the subsystem and are not-affected.
+- Debian does not backport new *features* (such as the image-sequence/track reading API)
+  into stable releases, so the vulnerable code will not be present in the trixie source
+  package either.
+
+---
+
+*Verdict: CVE-2026-32739 is a **false positive for Debian trixie (libheif 1.19.8)** — the
+affected code (`Box_stts::get_sample_duration()`) was introduced in 1.20.0 and does not
+exist in the shipped version.*
Description: CVE-2026-32882 - Fix overlay image with alpha channels using wrong stride
 The alpha channel pixel offset was computed using in_stride (the color
 channel stride) instead of alpha_stride. When the alpha channel has a
 different stride than the color channel, this causes an out-of-bounds
 read leading to potential information disclosure or crash.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/22b6266bf03a9f016f84a9b57b80e1dd7c79d64a
Author: Dirk Farin <dirk.farin@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-03-15

--- a/libheif/pixelimage.cc
+++ b/libheif/pixelimage.cc
@@ -1328,7 +1328,7 @@
         for (uint32_t x = in_x0; x < in_w; x++) {
           uint8_t* outptr = &out_p[out_x0 + (out_y0 + y - in_y0) * out_stride + x];
           uint8_t in_val = in_p[in_x0 + y * in_stride + x];
-          uint8_t alpha_val = alpha_p[in_x0 + y * in_stride + x];
+          uint8_t alpha_val = alpha_p[in_x0 + y * alpha_stride + x];

           *outptr = (uint8_t) ((in_val * alpha_val + *outptr * (255 - alpha_val)) / 255);
         }
